# .NET Framework → .NET 8 Migration: `BackgroundProcessor`

## Critical Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Never raised** — catch block is dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `volatile bool` for signaling | Works, but `CancellationToken` is idiomatic and superior |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerThread = new Thread(ProcessLoop) { IsBackground = true };
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — replaces ThreadAbortException handler
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop cleanly
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel(); // signals all cooperating code immediately

        // Join with timeout instead of Sleep + Abort
        if (_workerThread?.IsAlive == true && !_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time — log a warning.
            // There is NO equivalent to Abort() in .NET 8.
            // You must fix GetNextItem/ProcessItem to honor the token.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

**1. Blocking calls that ignore the token** — The #1 migration failure. If `GetNextItem()` blocks on a socket/queue that doesn't accept a `CancellationToken`, `Stop()` will hang. You **must** plumb the token into every blocking API:

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework) — could be force-killed by Abort()
var item = queue.Take();

// After (.NET 8) — cooperative cancellation
var item = queue.Take(cancellationToken); // throws OperationCanceledException
```

**2. No fallback for uncooperative code.** In Framework, `Abort()` was a safety net. In .NET 8, if a thread won't respond to cancellation, your only options are:
- Fix the code to honor the token (preferred)
- Run it in a **separate process** and kill the process
- Use `Environment.Exit()` as a last resort during app shutdown

**3. `Thread.Join()` replaces `Thread.Sleep()` + `IsAlive` check.** `Join` actually waits for thread completion rather than sleeping an arbitrary duration and re-checking.

**4. `ResetAbort()` had no analog** — it was needed because `ThreadAbortException` auto-rethrew at the end of catch blocks. `OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception with no such behavior, so no reset is needed.

## Consider `BackgroundService` Instead

For hosted apps (ASP.NET Core, Worker Services), the idiomatic .NET 8 approach is:

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }
}
```

This integrates with the host lifetime, dependency injection, and graceful shutdown automatically — no manual thread management needed.
